text=:Category: Varia%0a:Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a:Title: Power of Language in Surveys%0a:Author: yuluz%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 09:35%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-013915-901400#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 18:39-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-013915-901400#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe choice of language in survey questions can have implicit biases that skew the responses.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn marketing class, we are taught to watch our language choice when designing surveys to avoid biases that would invalidate the results. One example the professor gave in class was Trump's Inaugural Year Approval Poll. The first question on the survey is:%0a%0aHow would you rate President Trump's first year in office(2017)?%0aOption 1: Great%0aOption 2: Good %0aOption 3: Okay%0aOption 4: Other%0a%0aThe available answer options only cover the positive half of the performance scale and skims over the negative half with the single choice "other". Even when respondents selected "other" and think that "other" means "bad", the survey maker could still argue that "other" is a neutral word and does not necessarily means "bad". %0a%0aIn contrast, the second question of the survey asks about Obama's performance and goes as follows:%0a%0aHow would you rate President Obama's first year in office(2009)?%0aOption 1: Great%0aOption 2: Good %0aOption 3: Okay%0aOption 4: Poor%0aOption 5: Other%0a%0aBy explicitly putting the option "poor" as one of the choices, the survey maker could make the fraudulent case like some people think Obama did poorly during his first year in office while nobody think Trump did poorly during the first year, so Trump is a better president.  %0a%0aHere is a news article talking about Trump's biased inaugural year approval poll: https://www.newsweek.com/trump-fake-poll-doesnt-let-americans-disapprove-white-house-764804%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
